  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Traditionally difficult to prosecute due to lack of specific legal frameworks\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major anti-money laundering legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of large cash transactions\n\n3. International Progression:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- First comprehensive international framework addressing money laundering\n- Established money laundering as a criminal offense\n\n4. FATF Establishment (1989):\n- Financial Action Task Force created\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for national regulations\n\n5. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Patriot Act (2001) - Expanded anti-money laundering provisions\n- Enhanced international cooperation and information sharing\n\n6. Modern Regulatory Landscape:\n- Increasingly sophisticated legal frameworks\n- Expanded scope beyond traditional financial institutions\n- Growing emphasis on cryptocurrency and digital transaction monitoring\n\nThe field continues to evolve with technological and financial innovations.",
